<subsection xml:id="subsec-matrices">
  <title>Matrices</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Matrices provide a convenient way to organize numerical data in rows and columns. They are used to describe systems of linear equations, to encode linear transformations, and to model input-output relations in engineering, economics, and the natural sciences.
    </p>
    <p>
      In these notes, vectors are regarded as column vectors. Therefore, a vector in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> can also be viewed as an <m>(n\times 1)</m>-matrix.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <definition xml:id="def-matrix">
    <title>Matrix, Rows, and Columns</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A <term>matrix</term> is a rectangular array of real numbers arranged in rows and columns. A matrix with <m>m</m> rows and <m>n</m> columns is called an <term><m>(m\times n)</m>-matrix</term>. The set of all real <m>(m\times n)</m>-matrices is denoted by <m>\mathbb{R}^{m\times n}</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        A matrix <m>A \in \mathbb{R}^{m\times n}</m> is written in the form
        <me>
          A =
          \begin{pmatrix}
            a_{11} &amp; a_{12} &amp; \dots &amp; a_{1n} \\
            a_{21} &amp; a_{22} &amp; \dots &amp; a_{2n} \\
            \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; &amp; \vdots \\
            a_{m1} &amp; a_{m2} &amp; \dots &amp; a_{mn}
          \end{pmatrix}.
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        The entry in the <m>i</m>-th row and <m>j</m>-th column is denoted by <m>a_{ij}</m>. We also write <m>A=(a_{ij})</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <m>i</m>-th row of <m>A</m> is
        <me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            a_{i1} &amp; a_{i2} &amp; \dots &amp; a_{in}
          \end{pmatrix},
        </me>
        and the <m>j</m>-th column of <m>A</m> is
        <me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            a_{1j} \\
            a_{2j} \\
            \vdots \\
            a_{mj}
          \end{pmatrix}.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <example xml:id="ex-matrix-example">
    <title>An Example of a Matrix</title>
    <p>
      The matrix
      <me>
        A =
        \begin{pmatrix}
          2 &amp; -1 &amp; 4 \\
          0 &amp; 3 &amp; 5
        \end{pmatrix}
      </me>
      has <m>2</m> rows and <m>3</m> columns, so <m>A \in \mathbb{R}^{2\times 3}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Its entry in the first row and third column is <m>a_{13}=4</m>. The second row is
      <m>\begin{pmatrix} 0 &amp; 3 &amp; 5 \end{pmatrix}</m>, and the first column is
      <m>\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}</m>.
    </p>
  </example>

  <definition xml:id="def-matrix-equality">
    <title>Equality of Matrices</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Two matrices <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are equal if they have the same size and if all corresponding entries are equal.
      </p>
      <p>
        Thus, for <m>A=(a_{ij})</m> and <m>B=(b_{ij})</m>, we have <m>A=B</m> exactly if <m>a_{ij}=b_{ij}</m> for all <m>i</m> and <m>j</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-matrix-operations">
    <title>Arithmetic Operations on Matrices</title>

    <p>
      We now introduce the basic arithmetic operations for matrices.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-matrix-addition">
      <title>Addition and Scalar Multiplication</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A=(a_{ij})</m> and <m>B=(b_{ij})</m> be matrices of the same size in <m>\mathbb{R}^{m\times n}</m>, and let <m>\lambda \in \mathbb{R}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The <term>sum</term> of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> is defined component-wise by
          <me>
            A+B = (a_{ij}+b_{ij}).
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          The <term>scalar multiple</term> of <m>A</m> by <m>\lambda</m> is defined by
          <me>
            \lambda A = (\lambda a_{ij}).
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example xml:id="ex-matrix-addition-scalar">
      <title>Addition and Scalar Multiplication</title>
      <p>
        Let
        <me>
          A=
          \begin{pmatrix}
            1 &amp; 2 \\
            -1 &amp; 3
          \end{pmatrix},
          \qquad
          B=
          \begin{pmatrix}
            4 &amp; 0 \\
            2 &amp; -5
          \end{pmatrix}.
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Then
        <me>
          A+B=
          \begin{pmatrix}
            1+4 &amp; 2+0 \\
            -1+2 &amp; 3+(-5)
          \end{pmatrix}
          =
          \begin{pmatrix}
            5 &amp; 2 \\
            1 &amp; -2
          \end{pmatrix}.
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Moreover,
        <me>
          3A=
          \begin{pmatrix}
            3 &amp; 6 \\
            -3 &amp; 9
          \end{pmatrix}.
        </me>
      </p>
    </example>

    <definition xml:id="def-transposed-matrix">
      <title>Transpose</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A=(a_{ij}) \in \mathbb{R}^{m\times n}</m>. The <term>transpose</term> of <m>A</m> is the matrix <m>A^T \in \mathbb{R}^{n\times m}</m> obtained by interchanging rows and columns.
        </p>
        <p>
          In other words, the entry in row <m>j</m> and column <m>i</m> of <m>A^T</m> is <m>a_{ij}</m>. Thus,
          <me>
            (A^T)_{ji}=a_{ij}.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example xml:id="ex-transpose">
      <title>Computing a Transpose</title>
      <p>
        For
        <me>
          A=
          \begin{pmatrix}
            1 &amp; 4 &amp; -2 \\
            0 &amp; 3 &amp; 5
          \end{pmatrix},
        </me>
        the transpose is
        <me>
          A^T=
          \begin{pmatrix}
            1 &amp; 0 \\
            4 &amp; 3 \\
            -2 &amp; 5
          \end{pmatrix}.
        </me>
      </p>
    </example>

    <p>
        Matrix multiplication is the most important operation involving matrices. At first sight, its definition may seem somewhat unintuitive. We therefore begin by defining the matrix product and illustrating it with an example. Later, in a range of applications, we will see that this definition is both natural and extremely useful.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-matrix-multiplication">
      <title>Matrix Multiplication</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A=(a_{ij}) \in \mathbb{R}^{m\times n}</m> and <m>B=(b_{jk}) \in \mathbb{R}^{n\times r}</m>. Then the product <m>AB</m> is defined, because the number of columns of <m>A</m> equals the number of rows of <m>B</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The product <m>AB</m> is an <m>(m\times r)</m>-matrix
          <me>
            C=(c_{ik}),
          </me>
          whose entries are given by
          <me>
            c_{ik}=a_{i1}b_{1k}+a_{i2}b_{2k}+\dots+a_{in}b_{nk}
            =
            \sum_{j=1}^n a_{ij}b_{jk}.
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          Equivalently, the entry <m>c_{ik}</m> is obtained as the scalar product of the <m>i</m>-th row of <m>A</m> and the <m>k</m>-th column of <m>B</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      Hence, the product <m>AB</m> is defined only if the inner dimensions agree: the number of columns of <m>A</m> must equal the number of rows of <m>B</m>.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="ex-matrix-multiplication">
      <title>Computing a Matrix Product</title>
      <p>
        Let
        <me>
          A=
          \begin{pmatrix}
            1 &amp; 2 \\
            3 &amp; 4
          \end{pmatrix},
          \qquad
          B=
          \begin{pmatrix}
            5 &amp; 1 \\
            6 &amp; 0
          \end{pmatrix}.
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Then
        <me>
          AB=
          \begin{pmatrix}
            1\cdot 5 + 2\cdot 6 &amp; 1\cdot 1 + 2\cdot 0 \\
            3\cdot 5 + 4\cdot 6 &amp; 3\cdot 1 + 4\cdot 0
          \end{pmatrix}
          =
          \begin{pmatrix}
            17 &amp; 1 \\
            39 &amp; 3
          \end{pmatrix}.
        </me>
      </p>
    </example>

    <p>
      Since vectors are regarded as column vectors, matrix multiplication also allows us to multiply a matrix by a vector.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-matrix-vector-product">
      <title>Matrix-Vector Product</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A \in \mathbb{R}^{m\times n}</m> and let <m>\mathbf{v} \in \mathbb{R}^n</m>. Interpreting <m>\mathbf{v}</m> as an <m>(n\times 1)</m>-matrix, the product <m>A\mathbf{v}</m> is defined and belongs to <m>\mathbb{R}^m</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example xml:id="ex-matrix-vector-product">
      <title>A Matrix-Vector Product</title>
      <p>
        Let
        <me>
          A=
          \begin{pmatrix}
            1 &amp; 2 \\
            3 &amp; 4
          \end{pmatrix},
          \qquad
          \mathbf{v}=
          \begin{pmatrix}
            5 \\
            6
          \end{pmatrix}.
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Then
        <me>
          A\mathbf{v}
          =
          \begin{pmatrix}
            1\cdot 5 + 2\cdot 6 \\
            3\cdot 5 + 4\cdot 6
          \end{pmatrix}
          =
          \begin{pmatrix}
            17 \\
            39
          \end{pmatrix}.
        </me>
      </p>
    </example>

    <p>
      The matrix-vector product can also be interpreted in terms of the columns of the matrix. If
      <me>
        A=
        \begin{pmatrix}
          \mathbf{a}_1 &amp; \dots &amp; \mathbf{a}_n \\
        \end{pmatrix}
      </me>
      (for example, if 
        <m> A = \begin{pmatrix}
            1 &amp; 2 \\
            3 &amp;  4
          \end{pmatrix} </m>, then
        <m> \mathbf{a}_1 = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}</m> and 
        <m> \mathbf{a}_2 = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix}</m>)
      and
      <me>
        \mathbf{v}=
        \begin{pmatrix}
          x_1 \\
          \vdots \\
          x_n
        \end{pmatrix},
      </me>
      then
      <me>
        A\mathbf{v}=x_1\mathbf{a}_1+\dots+x_n\mathbf{a}_n.
      </me>
      Thus, <m>A\mathbf{v}</m> is a linear combination of the columns of <m>A</m>.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="ex-population-movements">
      <title>Modelling Population Movements</title>
      <p>
        Consider a population distributed between suburban areas (<m>S</m>) and urban areas (<m>U</m>). Suppose that in one year, <m>97\%</m> of the suburban population remains in the suburban area and <m>3\%</m> moves to the urban area. Likewise, <m>95\%</m> of the urban population remains in the urban area and <m>5\%</m> moves to the suburban area.
      </p>
      <p>
        If
        <me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            p_{S,0} \\
            p_{U,0}
          \end{pmatrix}
        </me>
        denotes the population vector at the beginning of the year, then the population vector at the end of the year is
        <me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            p_{S,1} \\
            p_{U,1}
          \end{pmatrix}
          =
          \begin{pmatrix}
            0.97 &amp; 0.05 \\
            0.03 &amp; 0.95
          \end{pmatrix}
          \begin{pmatrix}
            p_{S,0} \\
            p_{U,0}
          \end{pmatrix}.
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        This is an example of a matrix-vector product describing the state update of a system.
      </p>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-sensor-calibration">
      <title>Sensor Calibration</title>
      <p>
        Suppose a sensor system records two raw values collected in the vector
        <me>
          \mathbf{x}=
          \begin{pmatrix}
            10 \\
            4
          \end{pmatrix}.
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        A calibration matrix
        <me>
          A=
          \begin{pmatrix}
            1.1 &amp; 0.2 \\
            0.05 &amp; 0.9
          \end{pmatrix}
        </me>
        transforms the raw measurements into corrected values:
        <me>
          A\mathbf{x}
          =
          \begin{pmatrix}
            1.1\cdot 10 + 0.2\cdot 4 \\
            0.05\cdot 10 + 0.9\cdot 4
          \end{pmatrix}
          =
          \begin{pmatrix}
            11.8 \\
            4.1
          \end{pmatrix}.
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Thus, matrices can be used to model calibration and coordinate transformations in engineering applications.
      </p>
    </example>

  </subsubsection>

  <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-special-matrices">
    <title>Special Matrices and Laws of Arithmetic</title>

    <definition xml:id="def-special-matrices">
      <title>Special Matrices</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Several classes of matrices occur frequently.
        </p>
        <dl>
          <li>
            <title>Zero Matrix</title>
            <p>
              A matrix all of whose entries are equal to zero.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <title>Square Matrix</title>
            <p>
              A matrix with the same number of rows and columns.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <title>Identity Matrix</title>
            <p>
              A square matrix whose diagonal entries are equal to <m>1</m> and whose off-diagonal entries are equal to <m>0</m>. It is denoted by <m>I</m> or, if the size matters, by <m>I_n</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <title>Diagonal Matrix</title>
            <p>
              A square matrix whose off-diagonal entries are all zero.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <title>Triangular Matrix</title>
            <p>
              A square matrix is called upper triangular if all entries below the main diagonal are zero, and lower triangular if all entries above the main diagonal are zero.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <title>Symmetric Matrix</title>
            <p>
              A square matrix <m>A</m> satisfying <m>A^T=A</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <title>Skew-Symmetric Matrix</title>
            <p>
              A square matrix <m>A</m> satisfying <m>A^T=-A</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </dl>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example xml:id="ex-special-matrices">
      <title>Examples of Special Matrices</title>
      <p>
        The matrices
        <me>
          0=
          \begin{pmatrix}
            0 &amp; 0 \\
            0 &amp; 0
          \end{pmatrix},
          \qquad
          I_2=
          \begin{pmatrix}
            1 &amp; 0 \\
            0 &amp; 1
          \end{pmatrix},
          \qquad
          D=
          \begin{pmatrix}
            2 &amp; 0 \\
            0 &amp; -3
          \end{pmatrix}
        </me>
        are a zero matrix, an identity matrix, and a diagonal matrix, respectively.
      </p>
      <p>
        Moreover,
        <me>
          U=
          \begin{pmatrix}
            1 &amp; 4 \\
            0 &amp; 2
          \end{pmatrix}
        </me>
        is upper triangular, and
        <me>
          S=
          \begin{pmatrix}
            2 &amp; 1 \\
            1 &amp; 5
          \end{pmatrix}
        </me>
        is symmetric.
      </p>
    </example>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-matrix-arithmetic">
      <title>Laws of Matrix Arithmetic</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A,B,C</m> be matrices of suitable sizes, and let <m>\lambda \in \mathbb{R}</m>. Then the following rules hold.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><p><term>Addition:</term> <m>A+B=B+A</m> and <m>(A+B)+C=A+(B+C)</m>, provided the matrices have the same size.</p></li>
          <li><p><term>Neutral and Inverse Elements:</term> <m>A+0=A</m> and <m>A+(-A)=0</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p><term>Associativity of Multiplication:</term> <m>(AB)C=A(BC)</m>, whenever all products are defined.</p></li>
          <li><p><term>Identity Matrix:</term> <m>AI=A</m> and <m>IA=A</m>, where <m>I</m> is the identity matrix of suitable size.</p></li>
          <li><p><term>Distributivity:</term> <m>A(B+C)=AB+AC</m> and <m>(A+B)C=AC+BC</m>, whenever the products are defined.</p></li>
          <li><p><term>Compatibility with Scalars:</term> <m>\lambda(AB)=(\lambda A)B=A(\lambda B)</m>.</p></li>
        </ul>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <remark xml:id="rem-commutativity">
      <title>Matrix Multiplication Is Not Commutative</title>
      <p>
        In general, matrix multiplication is not commutative. This means that even if both products <m>AB</m> and <m>BA</m> are defined, they need not be equal.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <example xml:id="ex-noncommutative-multiplication">
      <title>A Counterexample to Commutativity</title>
      <p>
        Let
        <me>
          A=
          \begin{pmatrix}
            1 &amp; 1 \\
            0 &amp; 0
          \end{pmatrix},
          \qquad
          B=
          \begin{pmatrix}
            1 &amp; 0 \\
            1 &amp; 0
          \end{pmatrix}.
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Then
        <me>
          AB=
          \begin{pmatrix}
            2 &amp; 0 \\
            0 &amp; 0
          \end{pmatrix},
          \qquad
          BA=
          \begin{pmatrix}
            1 &amp; 1 \\
            1 &amp; 1
          \end{pmatrix}.
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Hence, <m>AB \neq BA</m>.
      </p>
    </example>
  </subsubsection>

